Adjusting a bit based on news that the Biden administration is trying to do something about the prices (https://www.reuters.com/business/energy/oil-prices-slide-biden-pushes-us-fuel-cost-cuts-2022-06-22/), although I am unconvinced it will be very effective.

Oil prices show no sign of weakness, and OPEC ministers don't seem to have any thoughts about significantly increasing production. But there are five months left for this question, the stock market is dropping fast, and a recession is a real possibility. A recession would likely cause oil prices to drop quite a lot, i.e., 50% or more. That is not in OPEC's interest. If OPEC wants to maximize oil revenue, IMHO, it should increase production now to force the price down and help avoid a recession. Of course I have no idea what oil ministers are thinking -- my thoughts are pure speculation. I'll move my bets to lower bins, and also flatten the distribution of the odds.

Brent crude futures rose past $108.5 per barrel on Wednesday, after falling over 5% in the previous session, lifted by declining US oil inventories and supply disruptions from Russia and Libya. The API report showed that US crude inventories decreased by about 4.5 million barrels last week, and if confirmed by official government data, would be the biggest drop in nationwide holdings since early February. Meanwhile, OPEC+ produced 1.45 million barrels per day below its production target in March as Russian output began to decline after sanctions imposed by the West. OPEC member Libya has been forced to shut down a number of oil facilities including the 300,000 bpd Sharara oilfield because of a wave of protests. However, a softer global economic outlook following Russias invasion of Ukraine and renewed virus lockdowns in China are weighing on prices.
Definitely oil producers would prefer the prices stay high.
